raid.bio:
Ayn Rand is an American writer and philosopher of Jewish origin originally from Russia, the creator of the philosophy of objectivism, and a two-time winner of the Prometheus Prize.

Ayn Rand, at the birth of Alisa Zinovievna Rosenbaum, was born on February 2, 1905 in St. Petersburg in a Jewish family of a pharmacist and dental technician, which is prosperous due to the fact that Ain's father in 1914 became the owner of a pharmacy in the city center.

The girl learned to read at the age of four, and a few years later she began to compose her first stories. At first, Alice studied at the women's gymnasium M. N. Stoyunina. But in 1917, after the revolution in Russia, her father's property was confiscated, and he had to move his family to the Crimea, where the girl graduated from school in Evpatoria.

On October 2, 1921, Rand applied to Petrograd University for a degree in social pedagogy, in which she studied history, philology, and law. She graduated from an educational institution in 1924, and a year later, in the publishing series Popular Film Library, her first creation was published as a separate book - a story about the work of the popular silent film actress Paula Negri.

In 1925, Ayn was issued a student visa to the United States, and in February 1926 she came to Chicago, to the house of her mother's cousins. She then began working as an extra in Hollywood. In 1929, having married film actor Frank O'Connor, on March 13, 1931, she received American citizenship.

From 1927 to 1932, Ayn Rand worked as a waitress, newspaper subscription saleswoman, and dresser. And then she managed to sell the script "Red Pawn" to Universal Studios for one and a half thousand dollars. It was an excellent initial investment in the pursuit of literary creativity.

Ayn Rand: books
It is worth noting that the first story in English, "The Husband I Bought," Rand wrote back in 1926, as soon as she arrived in the United States, but it was not published until 1984. The first work that the public saw was the novel “We Are the Living” about the life of the dispossessed in the USSR, which Rand composed for six whole years: first it was appreciated by American readers in 1936, and a year later by English ones. But, alas, he did not cause a big response.

In 1942, the Mussolini regime, having identified criticism of Soviet communism in the novel, ordered it to be filmed without the knowledge of Ayn Rand. This was a big impetus to the subsequent popularity of the writer: the leading actors of Italian cinema starred in the film, and after its release, the total circulation of the book reached two million copies. Then brilliant works literally rained down from Ayn Rand's pen:

"Hymn" (1937);
"Source" (1943);
Atlas Shrugged (1957);
"For the New Intellectual" (1961);
"The Virtue of Selfishness" (1964);
Capitalism: An Unknown Ideal (1966);
The New Left: An Anti-Industrial Revolution (1971);
"Introduction to the Philosophy of Knowledge of Objectivism" (1979);
"Philosophy: Who Needs It" (1982).
Ayn Rand died of heart failure on March 6, 1982. Buried at Kensico Cemetery in Valhalla, New York.
